ssage, or\n   exact historical claim, drill down before answering.\n5. To drill down, rerun `skim` with `--json` to get the relevant `session_key`\n   and `turn_key`, then use `show`.\n6. Use `show <session-key>` for turn-level context.\n7. Use `show <session-key> --turn <turn-key>` only for turns that need exact detail.\n8. Use `sessions` only when you need a session inventory or want to compare\n   \n[TRUNCATED]\nplanned, attempted, or\nchanged in this work?\"\n\nHuman output is intentionally compact but includes every related session and\nevery turn in chronological order. JSON output keeps\nfull `session_key` and `turn_key` values so you can drill into `show` without\nprinting those handles to the user.\n\nThe skim is a compressed table of contents. It abbreviates each turn but does\nnot omit related sessions or turns.\n\nUseful fields:\n\n- `target_kind` and `target_key`: target used for discovery.\n- `sessions`: related sessions in chronological order, with counts and previews.\n- `coverage`: shown sessions, shown turns, and direct related turn count.\n- `sessions[].turns`: every turn in order, with labels and previews.\n\nIf `skim` has enough context for a lightweight answer, summarize from it and\nstop. If it is ambiguous or misses the why, use JSON skim handles and drill\ndown with `show`.\n\n## Reading `sessions`\n\nUse `sessions` to answer which captured sessions are probably relevant.\n\nHere `review` means a GitButler review target, usually backed by a pull request\nor merge request. It does not mean \"perform a code review\". Keep `review` as\nthe target kind even when the value is a PR/MR-style key.\n\nUseful fields:\n\n- `session_key`: handle for follow-up reads.\n- `latest_captured_at`: freshness signal.\n- `record_count` and `turn_count`: size estimate before hydration.\n- `related_turn_keys`: direct target evidence.\n- `match_evidence`: why the session was returned.\n- `observed_targets`: branch, review/PR/MR, or change keys observed in related turns.\n- `latest_user_preview` and `latest_assistant_preview`: quick intent/result scan.\n\nRelated sessions are sorted by latest activity.\n\n## Reading `show`\n\nUse `show` to open a session or one turn.\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog show <session-key> --limit 20\nbut agentlog show <session-key> --turn <turn-key> --limit 50\n```\n\nWithout `--turn`, `show` answers what happened in a session at turn granularity.\n\nUseful fields:\n\n- `coverage`: returned turns versus total turns.\n- `turn_key`: handle for `show --turn`.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-21T05:21:32.912Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}